      • hasName

        public boolean hasName()
        Description copied from class: SailPointObject
        Return true if the object has a name. This is used by the AbstractSailPointObject and the PersistenceManagers to tell if the name can be used in a search filter.

        It is almost always true, but a few classes like log records do not have meaningful names. Consider using ObjectUtil.hasName(SailPointContext, Class) instead

        Overrides:
        hasName in class SailPointObject

      • getUniqueKeyProperties

        public java.lang.String[] getUniqueKeyProperties()
        Description copied from class: SailPointObject
        Return a list of property names other than "id" that combined make up a unique identifier for this object. If the value is null, and isNameUnique is true it is assumed that "name" is the unique key. This is overloaded in a few subclasses where name alone is not a unique key. One example is ManagedAttribute which are identified by the combination of _application, _attribute, and _value properties. This is only used when importing files of XML that do not contain unique database ids. To prevent duplicates, first objects must be matched by name or unique key combination before new objects are created.
        Overrides:
        getUniqueKeyProperties in class SailPointObject
